INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (274001, 'The widespread willingness to rely on thermonuclear bombs as the ultimate weapon displays a cavalier attitude toward death that has always puzzled me. My impression is that...most of the defenders of these weapons are not suitably horrified at the possibility of a war in which hundreds of millions of people would be killed...I suspect that an important factor may be belief in an afterlife, and that the proporttion of those who think that death is not the end is much higher among the partisans of the bomb than among its opponents.', 2595, 0), (274002, 'When you will have to search for long to collect other nine players to organize your usual five-a-side football match..you will realize to be old...', 46879, 0), (274003, 'The ritual works. The forms overcome doubts. We have learned over the centuries to weave meaning around emptiness and pain. A meaning and a pattern. We have been practising that for a very long time.', 43090, 0), (274004, 'When you''re already going through a rough patch of life', 46880, 0), (274005, 'There is a wilderness we walk aloneHowever well-companioned', 44447, 0), (274006, 'I love you just the way you arebut you don''t see you like I do.You shouldn''t try so hard to be perfect.Trust me, perfect should try to be you.', 2383, 0), (274007, 'Poetry can be dangerous, especially beautiful poetry, because it gives the illusion of having had the experience without actually going through it.', 58, 0), (274008, 'Sometimes when I''m aloneI Cry, Cause I am on my own.The tears I cry are bitter and warm.They flow with life but take no formI Cry because my heart is torn.I find it difficult to carry on. If I had an ear to confide in, I would cry among my treasured friend, but who do you know that stops that long, to help another carry on.The world moves fast and it would rather pass by.Then to stop and see what makes one cry, so painful and sad. And sometimes...I Cry and no one cares about why.', 1097, 0), (274009, 'All things want to float.', 36, 0), (274010, 'All that we see and seem is but a dream within a dream.', 49, 0), (274011, 'The clouds above us join and separate,The breeze in the courtyard leaves and returns.Life is like that, so why not relax?Who can stop us from celebrating?', 46881, 0), (274012, 'For what is a dream if not love first felt and what is mystery if not life itself', 46882, 0), (274013, 'Take the blinders from your visiontake the padding from your earsand confess you''ve heard me crying and admit you''ve seen my tears.', 74, 0), (274014, 'When I talk of taking a trip I mean forever.', 809, 0), (274015, 'Eggshells become hard to break after walking on them for so long.', 46883, 0), (274016, 'To do something very common, in my own way.', 809, 0), (274017, 'A robin redbreast in a cagePuts all heaven in a rage.A dove-house fill''d with doves and pigeonsShudders hell thro'' all its regions.A dog starv''d at his master''s gatePredicts the ruin of the state.A horse misused upon the roadCalls to heaven for human blood.Each outcry of the hunted hareA fibre from the brain does tear.A skylark wounded in the wing,A cherubim does cease to sing.The game-cock clipt and arm''d for fightDoes the rising sun affright.Every wolf''s and lion''s howlRaises from hell a human soul.- "Auguries of Innocence', 221, 0), (274018, 'I will arise and go now, for always night and day I hear lake water lapping...I hear it in the deep heart''s core.', 276, 0), (274019, 'Only union with you gives joy. The rest if tearing down one building to put up another.', 58, 0), (274020, 'I’m going to become a beat poet and a lesbian!', 8019, 0), (274021, 'I feel my griefs too, and there scarce is groundUpon my flesh t''inflict another wound.Yet dare I not complain, or wish for deathWith holy Paul; lest it be thought the breathOf discontent; or that these prayers beFor weariness of life, not love of thee.', 29394, 0), (274022, 'PricklyWhen I''m feelingporcupine-y,I get nasty,I get whiny.Stay away orI might stick you.My sharp words arequills to prick you.', 13979, 0), (274023, 'I eat the hearts of girls and puke slugs and snails.', 8814, 0), (274024, 'Even the simplest poemMay destroy your immunity to human emotions.All poems must carry a Government warning. WordsCan seriously affect your heart.', 46884, 0), (274025, 'i carry your heart with me(i carry it inmy heart)i am never without it(anywherei go you go,my dear;and whatever is doneby only me is your doing,my darling)', 37, 0), (274026, 'Ring out, wild bells, to the wild sky,The flying cloud, the frosty light;The year is dying in the night;Ring out, wild bells, and let him die.Ring out the old, ring in the new,Ring, happy bells, across the snow:The year is going, let him go;Ring out the false, ring in the true.', 25, 0), (274027, 'He who mocks the infant''s faithShall be mock''d in age and death.He who shall teach the child to doubtThe rotting grave shall ne''er get out.He who respects the infant''s faithTriumphs over hell and death.The child''s toys and the old man''s reasonsAre the fruits of the two seasons.- "Auguries of Innocence', 221, 0), (274028, 'I is for immortality, which for some poets is a necessary compensation. Presumably miserable in this life, they will be remembered when the rest of us are long forgotten. None of them asks about the quality of that remembrance--what it will be like to crouch in the dim hallways of somebody''s mind until the moment of recollection occurs, or to be lifted off suddenly and forever into the pastures of obscurity. Most poets know better than to concern themselves with such things. They know the chances are better than good that their poems will die when they do and never be heard of again, that they''ll be replaced by poems sporting a new look in a language more current. They also know that even if individual poems die, though in some cases slowly, poetry will continue: that its subjects, it constant themes, are less liable to change than fashions in language, and that this is where an alternate, less lustrous immortality might be. We all know that a poem can influence other poems, remain alive in them, just as previous poems are alive in it. Could we not say, therefore, that individual poems succeed most by encouraging revisions of themselves and inducing their own erasure? Yes, but is this immortality, or simply a purposeful way of being dead?', 5859, 0), (274029, 'Reluctant hero, drafted again each Fourthof July, I''ll bow and remember you. Whoshall we follow next? Who shall we killnext time?', 1192, 0), (274030, 'PoetTo mask the fiery thought,in simple words succeeds.For still the craft of genius is,To mask a king in weeds', 760, 0), (274031, 'The stars are but tears shed by a miriad of unrequited dreams', 46885, 0), (274032, 'Thoughts as warm as a silky summer rain, flowing over the edge of my soul''s gentle.not tides returning them along the shoreline to laughing gulls.', 14261, 0), (274033, 'fortune has no era finer than this moment', 46886, 0), (274034, 'It is right it should be so;Man was made for joy and woe;And when this we rightly know,Thro'' the world we safely go.Joy and woe are woven fine,A clothing for the soul divine.Under every grief and pineRuns a joy with silken twine.- "Auguries of Innocence', 221, 0), (274035, 'The emmet''s inch and eagle''s mileMake lame philosophy to smile.He who doubts from what he seesWill ne''er believe, do what you please.- "Auguries of Innocence', 221, 0), (274036, 'Oh, the summer night / HAS A SMILE OF LIGHT / And she sits on a sapphire throne.', 46887, 0), (274037, 'So, the world happens twice--once what we see it as;second it legends itselfdeep, the way it is.', 1192, 0), (274038, 'People are looking for chimes and resonances. Chimes leave echoes, and that''s what rhyme is. Poetry is about leaving an echo imprint in somebody else''s head, in the dark snow of their mind.', 46888, 0), (274039, 'Unlike the bough that shook off her dead leaves violentlylike a wet terrier,unlike the beating of the butterfly, her wings, against the cocoon, some dreams never made a move.', 6628, 0), (274040, '. . . distant as the death of grocery chickens.', 46889, 0), (274041, 'The morning slathers its whateveracross the thing.', 12099, 0), (274042, 'Blessed is the covenant of love, the covenant of mercy, useless light behind the terror, deathless song in the house of night.', 571, 0), (274043, 'Blessed are you who circled desire with a blade, and the garden with fiery swords, and heaven and earth with a word.', 571, 0), (274044, 'Poetry should be like ''Uh-huh. Baby has to have it.', 46890, 0), (274045, 'O to be self-balanced for contingencies, to confront night, storms, hunger, ridicule, accidents, rebuffs, as the trees and animals do.', 1127, 0), (274046, 'Should I get lost, just point me in the direction of a poem.', 46891, 0), (274047, 'Though I love your company, your instructions are wasted her. I will always choose the woman who caries me off, I will always sit with the family of loneliness.', 571, 0), (274048, 'The greatness of poetry comes from its struggle to express the rapture of the soul in the contemplation of beauty.', 46892, 0), (274049, 'If I wouldn''t of spent so much time shooting spit wads at my English teacher I''d know how to punctuate good thing I normally write poetry.', 3034, 0), (274050, 'I''d rather write poetry than watch TV it allows me to share the wide screen in me.', 3034, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (274051, 'Some poems are written great, some poems are written swell. But then there are poems that could win a prize in Hell.', 3034, 0), (274052, 'the light too brief to finish any work —the woman seeks to amplify the dark', 46893, 0), (274053, 'I have a book of poetry I believe many should read but in each verse you''ll discover it wasn''t written for greed.', 3034, 0), (274054, 'Des Menschen Kraft, im Dichter offenbartThe human power is revealed by poetIl potere dell''umanità si rivela nel poeta', 282, 0), (274055, 'When you are lost in the right way, you don''t go back to being found in the wrong way.', 4549, 0), (274056, 'They say she is too much to handle, but when the moon pulls the tide and the wolves howl her name, blessed are the ones who have been taken by her wild.', 6343, 0), (274057, 'Some people wait to get flowers while others grow gardens.', 46894, 0), (274058, 'Decide if a poem is a question or a declaration, a meditation or an outcry.', 5867, 0), (274059, 'Etched In Bone-At night I engrave my bones with poems.Scratching.Carving.Etching.During the day I feel every notch and ridgehidden inside me.I repeat them to myself.In time others will read them tooand know me.', 40256, 0), (274060, 'I am a hoarder of words, a giver of them, too', 7493, 0), (274061, 'By noon, silence arrives one last time, flowing into every space of her room. And before long, silence swallows sound and color and seconds and equations and entire stanzas of old poetry, leaving new words. The sheets are breathless. The room is bruised.My mother is still warm.', 3601, 0), (274062, 'Poetry, to me, is a type of shamanistic chant capable of chasing away the darkness within us.', 19949, 0), (274063, 'Poetry is an old wise serpent which only occasionally comes out to catch the sun (and scare people).', 19949, 0), (274064, 'Man is in his own microcosm akin to a personal box, with poetry as its lid which it can defend itself from the world', 19949, 0), (274065, 'Some people are like the fragrance of flowers!', 5535, 0), (274066, 'Why do I love poetry? It''s more than word play, less about the pay. Let''s just say that for the first time in along while I stopped running, stared back at my darkest worst and said, ''Come here, you belong with me', 4545, 0), (274067, 'Why do I love poetry? It''s more than word play, less about the pay. Let''s just say that for the first time in a long while I stopped running, stared back at my darkest worst and said, ''Come here, you belong with me', 4545, 0), (274068, 'Over the mountain growths, disease and sorrow,	 An uncaught bird is ever hovering, hovering,High in the purer, happier air.', 1127, 0), (274069, 'Now came still evening on, and twilight grayHad in her sober livery all things clad;Silence accompany''d; for beast and bird,They to their grassy couch, these to their nests,Were slunk, all but the wakeful nightingale;She all night long her amorous descant sung;Silence was pleas''d. Now glow''d the firmamentWith living sapphires; Hesperus, that ledThe starry host, rode brightest, till the moon,Rising in clouded majesty, at lengthApparent queen unveil''d her peerless light,And o''er the dark her silver mantle threw.', 465, 0), (274070, 'I never understood desire until i felt your hands around my throat.', 10117, 0), (274071, 'Cliche is Truth''s most loyal friend...', 46895, 0), (274072, '... time is how you spend your love ...', 8796, 0), (274073, 'Naked PoetryWhen it comes to undressing poetry,we are often required to placenude pics of our soulsin virtual ink!', 15187, 0), (274074, 'Poetry is the yearning of the soul to break free!', 5535, 0), (274075, 'You''re Times New Roman, but I''m more Comic Sans.', 46896, 0), (274076, 'A man does not become a real man by showing his physical domination over women. A man becomes a real man by loving, respecting and protecting women.', 5535, 0), (274077, 'Poetry is the lighthouse of lifeGuiding the lost from a stormy sea.Without it''s presence darkness prevailsKeeping us from all we can be.People write poetry because they have no choiceAnswering to the call of their gift.Where some tend to pull their readers downOthers compose to give them a lift.excerpts from The Power of Poetry by Tom Zart', 46897, 0), (274078, 'I heard the breeze whisper your name to the trees. And the flowers giggled smiling at the leaves. I and my loneliness keep talking about you.', 5535, 0), (274079, 'She day-dreams just as I do. She is addicted to her solitude just as I am. She loves watching the rain-drops fall slowly on to the green leaves of an old guava tree just as I do. She loves drifting in time and time travel just as I do. She loves looking at the waves dashing against the rocks just as I do.', 5535, 0), (274080, 'A strange feeling of lonelinessAdrift near the blue canvasYou may stare long and listen deepYet not know whether sea-shore or sea-snore!', 5535, 0), (274081, 'I am trying to both be happy and pay attention to the world around me. I do not know if it is possible to do both at the same time.', 28384, 0), (274082, 'Don’t you dare say these times are hollowJust because there are storms raging by.Just lay low on your pillow,Close your eyes and say goodbyeTo the world that you lived in today.Let your dreams carry you away;You lived a nightmare all through the day,It is time to dream, so don’t delay.You searched for a reason to live,Yes darling, you searched everywhere.You had to push, you had to strive,It is time now to get some air.You searched in all that is outside,It is time now to look inside,Cause that is where you’ll findA reason worth keeping in your mind.These dreams are not an escape, darling,You need time to see past the lies that blind you.It is time for you to start runningTo those things that are true.So, don’t you dare say these nights are hollow,Just because there are storms raging by.Just lay low on your pillowAnd lose yourself in this lullaby.', 7609, 0), (274083, '& besides, I don’tdesign my smiles to be nets because I’m not fishing', 46898, 0), (274084, 'Truth is everywhere, and easily seen.Believing one’s eyesIs the difficulty.', 46899, 0), (274085, 'Cover mine eyes, O my Love! Mine eyes that are weary of bliss As of light that is poignant and strong O silence my lips with a kiss, My lips that are weary of song! Shelter my soul, O my love! My soul is bent low with the pain And the burden of love, like the grace Of a flower that is smitten with rain: O shelter my soul from thy face!', 25703, 0), (274086, 'Everything is connected. We see the signs every moment. There are miracles waiting to happen!', 5535, 0), (274087, 'If I could claw the words out of the back of my throat and give them, dripping of me, to you, we would talk of sticky hands, and the messes they make.', 6343, 0), (274088, 'You were the devil. Dressed in everything. I wanted.', 18271, 0), (274089, 'No one leaves home unless homes is the mouth of a shark.', 483, 0), (274090, 'I think you feel like, unless you''re damagedyou''re not deep enough or mysterious enoughor complicated enough to ever be appreciated by another.And that is deeply untrue.', 12107, 0), (274091, 'It took me a long time to realise that mothers are women who carry youAnd not necessarily in their womb.', 12107, 0), (274092, 'Lift up your eyes unto mine air and see the love floating there for I am Paradise and I am everywhere.', 46900, 0), (274093, 'These poems are cupsthat I pour my love into.Here, Drink!', 3588, 0), (274094, 'She is the light,at the end of this endless tunnel.', 16915, 0), (274095, 'No misery ever so beautiful than the one this mind creates.', 16915, 0), (274096, 'You burn like a candleinside my soul,showing me a waythrough this darkness.', 16915, 0), (274097, 'Amidst a crowd of strangers,I still remain unknownto myself.', 16915, 0), (274098, 'Tingling fingers, morning birds, rain splatters on window pane, journals of fading escapades and laughter...', 8514, 0), (274099, 'Never be an artist that starts worshiping yourself or believe your little group is better than anyone outside of it. For, you are nothing more than a grain of sand on a hillside in this world of ours. Even Da Vinci’s work is only glanced at then scrolled past on a phone or computer these days. Climb down off your throne and become humble once more.', 9017, 0), (274100, 'The mind is a poetic meadow for reification, where dark and light things are created', 8514, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (274101, 'We all have our state of mind-		happy or sad,sources of both are so relatable.Despite showing someone’s faults & flaws we need to cherish them. cause, we all are into an 	e n d l e s s l o o p.', 46901, 0), (274102, 'no one tells you rome is ending until you''re the last one standing alone in a coliseum where a city had been.', 46902, 0), (274103, 'Do tears not yet spilledwait in small lakes?Or are they invisible riversthat run toward sadness?', 12, 0), (274104, 'That woman wants to hear all my wishes,For already a thousand years,And each my thought knows to read,Even if I don''t utter it aloud.', 46903, 0), (274105, 'i asked him why he carried a flask."because the bottle pours too fucking slow', 46902, 0), (274106, 'Life provides the substance for poetry we just have to put it to paper', 46904, 0), (274107, 'Do not forget about the thorns on the roseswhen you say that love is like a red red rose.', 26792, 0), (274108, 'I have wished a bird would fly away,And not sing by my house all day;Have clapped my hands at him from the doorWhen it seemed as if I could bear no more.The fault must partly have been in me.The bird was not to blame for his keys.And of course there must be something wrongIn waiting to silence any song.', 35, 0), (274109, 'But the sun will rise the day after tomorrowA millennium without us silences our last echoTo tiny fragments even our plastics are reducedIn Eden Reincarnate all life but ours is renewed', 20318, 0), (274110, 'Love is like a white geranium.It grows like a weedoverpowering the ground–if you don’t take care of itprune itshape itit climbs wallsand hidesinsectsthat slowly eat at itmaking it die.Easily grownand easily withered.', 26792, 0), (274111, 'Poetry is an attempt to penetrate the dense reality to find a place where the simplest things look as new as through the eyes of a child.', 1298, 0), (274112, 'Desire is a powerful boat herding anchors and chains in the middle of the night.', 46905, 0), (274113, 'I only live to love so manyFig trees but could neverSleep under one. One is tooLittle in one lifetime.', 46906, 0), (274114, 'We all knew she needed help.But none of us knew how.And none of us could swallow our pride and just ask her what she needed.I don’t know why.Maybe we were too ashamed we didn’t know how to approach our own mother.So we let the years slip unhappily past us and hoped we would never inherit the misery embedded in her soul.But I did.And I didn’t know how to say it aloud. And I still don’t.', 12107, 0), (274115, 'I can’t pinpoint the moment this all happened. The moment we broke. But we did.And it feels like acid in my throat.', 12107, 0), (274116, 'It always felt as though there were a shaken beehive living in my chest. I could never rest.', 12107, 0), (274117, 'I felt torn Between living and dying Between sleeping and surviving.', 12107, 0), (274118, 'At times poems can be like riddles, too difficult to decipher or comprehend. But how else does one come to understand what can only be felt but not said?', 15319, 0), (274119, 'You should be more carefulwhen you move, my dearwhat with you...spilling moonlightinto my poem, with a mereflick of your hand.', 1864, 0), (274120, 'With wine beside a gently flowing brook - this is the best', 46907, 0), (274121, 'Someone will remember us I sayEven in another time', 4920, 0), (274122, 'I''m two days away from day after tomorrowCounting the hours to my upcoming sorrow Suddenly I lookinto the eyes of my childThen all sadness goneas I smile the way she smiled', 2760, 0), (274123, 'Silence. First it’s a cloud of apricot trees in flower, yellow or ivory, like a thousand little butterflies sown in the fresh grass, moving in the glow of lamplight when night ascends. Fragments of dreams. You can see the red sun setting on the foliage, like an enormous mass of incandescent steel.Then there were the trees a little farther off, straightening their fragile frames, the woolen blue pincushion flower like an eye and that tumult of milk in the deep stone, and finally the moan of the air beaten by a flock of blue woodpigeons– a silken challenge perhaps, or one of crackled leather.', 46908, 0), (274124, 'Latefor the present, I supposeaccentuated each timeyou see, quick enoughthis fraction of earthunderfootthat upright speechimprints,like the whole of beingresumesWe’ve hit on something like lightning strikes', 46908, 0), (274125, 'And thenwe no longer distinguish far nor nearThey sleepdreamgather branchesfor this firethe cloud brewsagainst the powerless day —Long line of fugitivesbeneath the snow', 46908, 0), (274126, 'Everything had become song. The curve of the road beneath the clouds here, and there the strokes of dark earth, the green and the gray, the torn pink of clay and gravel under fingertips. The consonance was above all that of the muffled shadow and grass to the depths of sky, where a flutter of cheerful feathers quivered.In these dreams there are also black walnut trees, and then a forest that opens in a breeze. Nothing. Nothing more than the obstinate sound of wind.', 46908, 0), (274127, 'I exaggerateThere is a lie in my truthLook! My soul is blue', 20318, 0), (274128, 'Poems arrive. They hide in feelings and images, in weeds and delivery vans, daring us to notice and give them form with our words. They take us to an invisible world where light and dark, inside and outside meet.', 46909, 0), (274129, 'The Veil of Consciousness is a thin sheath thatI wear to view the transparency of the life thatSurrounds me.', 5577, 0), (274130, 'I crouch in cornersThe infection is widespreadLove epidemic', 20318, 0), (274131, 'Does my soul sufferWhen my body breaks downWhen I feel mortalWhen my body is weakDoes the soul rejoiceThe end is near', 20318, 0), (274132, 'No music in the raindropsNo clouds with silver liningTorrents of sorrowsHorror in streams', 20318, 0), (274133, 'heopened me uplike a book& poured thepoetryback i', 6656, 0), (274134, 'May the nights always be aglowwith the bliss of the daywith unharmed hands and feetand kissed cheeks.', 1864, 0), (274135, 'The mere ambition to write a poem is enough to kill it.', 10478, 0), (274136, 'This is hell, but I planned it. I sawed it,I nailed it, and I will live in it until it kills me.I can nail my left palm to the left-hand crosspiece butI can’t do everything myself. I need a hand to nail the right,a help, a love, a you, a wife.', 46910, 0), (274137, 'Alas! this is not what I thought life was.I knew that there were crimes and evil men,Misery and hate; nor did I hope to passUntouched by suffering, through the rugged glen.In mine own heart I saw as in a glassThe hearts of others ... And whenI went among my kind, with triple brassOf calm endurance my weak breast I armed,To bear scorn, fear, and hate, a woeful mass!', 165, 0), (274138, 'No Brasil não há outonomas as folhas caem- In Brazil there is no autumnbut the leaves fall', 46911, 0), (274139, 'Poetry is not only to write but to express our feelings.', 46912, 0), (274140, 'God’s justice in the one, and his goodness in the other, is exercised for evermore, as the everlasting subjects of his reward and punishment.', 46913, 0), (274141, 'Poetry is not for poets, poetry lovers or perceived poetic persons only. Poetry is in yourself, others and everything of nature and man-made.Poetry may not be a solution, yet it can reveal or ease challenges faced.Poetry is capable of affecting any heart.', 9382, 0), (274142, 'Sorrows of Werther William Makepeace Thackeray (1811–63) WERTHER had a love for Charlotte  Such as words could never utter; Would you know how first he met her?  She was cutting bread and butter. Charlotte was a married lady, 5  And a moral man was Werther, And for all the wealth of Indies  Would do nothing for to hurt her. So he sigh’d and pin’d and ogled,  And his passion boil’d and bubbled, 10 Till he blew his silly brains out,  And no more was by it troubled. Charlotte, having seen his body  Borne 